Anchoring - Represents the position of a parameter in a matched filename.  Each anchoring
	is represented by two numbers, representing the start and end position of the
	match.  Anchorings are represented as arrays of integers of length 2*N, where N is
	the number of parameters.  For instance, when "/usr/bin" is matched to
	"/$DIR/$NAME", the anchoring is given by the array [1 4 5 8].

Command - A command that is run for a target.  Enclosed by braces ({}) in Stu files, and
	executed with the shell.

Content rule - A rule of the form "A = {xxx}".  Stu will write "xxx" into the file A,
	effectively hardcoding the content of the file into the Stu file.

Copy rule - A rule of the form "A = B;", which copies file B to file A.

Depth - The depth of a dependency counts how many times over it includes a dynamic
	dependency.  For instance, an ordinary file target "file" has depth zero, a
	dynamic dependency "[file]" has depth one, a doubly dynamic dependency "[[file]]"
	has depth two.

Directive - A construct introduced with '%' in Stu source code.  Directives are processed
	before the source code is otherwise parsed.  They are comparable to C preprocessor
	directives, but do not implement a macro system.

File - An object in the file system.  We use the term in the broad
	sense, which includes directories and other special files.  The "normal"
	files which store a sequence of bytes are called regular files.

Flag - A flag is a syntax and semantic element of Stu scripts.  They start with
	a dash.  An example is '-p' for persistent dependencies.

Job - A job is a child process started by Stu to build one or more files or phony targets.
	Jobs are run in the background by default, but the -i option changes that.

Name - The name of a file or of a phony target.  Names are strings of bytes, must have
	length at least one, and cannot contain the NUL (\0) character.

Option - An option is passed on the Stu command line and starts with a dash.  Some have
	arguments.

Parameter - A parameter in the name of a file or a phony target; written as $name or
	${name}.  In the command, the corresponding environment variable is set by Stu.

Phony target - One of the two basic datatypes ("targets") of Stu, the other being files.
	They are noted with the '@' symbol, e.g., '@all'.  A phony target can be built
	like a file, but will not result in a built file.  A phony target can also be used
	only for its dependency.

Place - Filename + line number + column number.  Used to print error messages.

Placed - A class name starts with 'Place_' when it includes a place, e.g., 'Name'
	vs. 'Place_Name'.

Plain - (Said of a dependency or target) Either a file or a phony target.

Special rule - Special rules are used when matching parametrized targets to names of files
	and phony targets.  They are described in the manpage.

Target - A file or a phony target, possibly (multiply) dynamic.

Trace - A line printed by the TRACE() macro.  Enabled by $STU_TRACE.  Only in the debug
	variant.

Transient - A transient target is a phony whose rule (a) contains no file targets, and (b)
	has no command.  Transient targets pass some flags (-o -p) to their dependencies.

Variant - Stu can be compiled in different variants, e.g. ndebug, debug.  See
	doc/VARIANTS.
